dataIdInfo.suppInfo:
6-13-2012 Attributes "Why No Access" describe the reasons why No Pubuc Access has been assigned to each NPA property. Kathy Metivier GIS Technician.
1-23-2013 Attribute "MZD" represents the Management Zone Designation assigned in the SDE.Planning.Management Designation Areas feature class where AA is Agricultural Area, PRA is Passive Recreation Area, HCA is Habitat Conservation Area, and NA is Natural Area. Conditional MZD awaiting Board of Trustees and City Council approval is noted as AG_C, PRA_C, HCA_C, and NA_C. Null values in MZD represent no management designation yet assigned and TBD is to be determined. Where properties have multiple management areas the MZD attribute notes the categories alphabetically seperated by slash marks, eg. HCA/NA/PRA. This attribute allows query and spatial connectivity of management designation areas as assigned to each property. Kathy Metivier GIS Technician. PropNum is the future link between property and management designation zones.
3-19-13 Schnell IIa - property section on the west side of Boulder Canyon Dr - polygon split for road access. Incuded in HCA with Schnell II. Schnell IIb is the parking area south of the Red Lion and east of Boulder Canyon Dr and is not included in the HCA. Dogs allowed on Leash to Tenderfoot and continues as Voice and Sight. Multiuse trail in both directions allowed seven days a week.
3-21-13 The OSMP property boundary on the southern edge of 1265 CORP and RUDD-east along the northern edge of Marshall Lake extended 200 to 300 feet beyond the feature class fence line. As directed by Jim Schmitt of OSMP the property boundary was edited by Kathy Metivier and snapped to the fence line. 03-21-13 email from Jim: "Greetings: I believe that this particular boundary line confusion is just one part of the property line issues ( the legal descriptions do not match up with the fence lines in a number of areas surrounding Marshall Lake) that we tried to resolve with FRICO. That all ended up as part of the Community Ditch underpass lawsuit. The court case never did spend any significant time on these boundary line issues but Im pretty sure the Court ruled against FRICO on those issues. So who knows what the present status is of the lines no one. For now, I would urge us to respect the fence lines that are on the ground. Maybe now that FRICO has replaced its upper management team, we could re-open discussions with them to resolve all the boundary issues once and for all ?( If we deem it worthy of the effort.) Jim s".
5-31-13 1265 CORP property boundary is edited back to its original state, prior to the 3-21-13 changes, to reflect the management designation zone boundaries and 2006 study area. Once the fence lines are recalculated through GPS in 2013, OSMP staff may revisit the property boundary discrepancy at that time. KM.
7-11-13 Lindsay East Property: conflict with joint BOCO/OSMP CE data in attribute table. Linda Vandevort responded with this researched explanation: "I have researched the ownership of our Lindsay east property. The County owns it 100% and we have 10 CEs over the property. I think the reason the property has been confusing is that OSMP initially purchased Lindsay East from a private party with a BMPA note. Then the County purchased various parcels within the Lindsay East property from OSMP each year for 10 years by exercising options until they finally had purchased all of the parcels. Each time they purchased a parcel they gave the City a conservation easement over that particular parcel that is why there are so many CEs. Linda" I will change the GIS attribute to show BOCO ownership and BOCO managed with OSMP CE and <null> as MZD for LINDSAY and LINDSAY - East (small piece in Jefferson County).KM.
